WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.719
So the summary is that we decided last year to create a not-for-profit development group

00:00:16.719 --> 00:00:21.520
to work on the Apache Arrow project, which I will tell you about.

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:27.600
There's a number of reasons why we decided to do this.

00:00:27.600 --> 00:00:32.480
Partly because the Arrow project does involve the R world, but it involves the Python world

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:39.680
and many other programming language ecosystems, and we wanted to be able to build relationships

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:45.200
with many different companies around the world that want data science tools to become faster

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:48.759
and more scalable into the future.

00:00:48.759 --> 00:00:54.240
So Hadley and I are the leadership for the organization.

00:00:54.240 --> 00:01:01.840
We are now five full-time engineers, so we've got three people in North America, two people

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:07.760
in Europe, so Ben and Francois are here, so if you see them, please say hello.

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:14.639
Folks from the Tidyverse team are involved on a part-time basis to work on the R side

00:01:14.639 --> 00:01:17.080
of things.

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:23.760
We are still hiring, so if you know anyone who likes to work on database systems or likes

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:30.480
to do benchmarking and test and build automation, we have a lot of that to do, so please definitely

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:32.120
get in touch.

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:39.919
So as Tarif was saying in his keynote earlier today, RStudio has been really amazing in

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:46.459
helping us get this off the ground by essentially making it so that I don't have the overhead

00:01:46.459 --> 00:01:50.800
of having to run a company, can focus on doing software engineering.

00:01:50.839 --> 00:01:52.239
I used to work at Two Sigma.

00:01:52.239 --> 00:01:57.919
They're continuing to sponsor the work, and we've had NVIDIA and also the Open Data Science

00:01:57.919 --> 00:02:05.199
Conference join as sponsors for 2019, so NVIDIA just gave us some really high-end hardware

00:02:05.199 --> 00:02:09.979
to do testing for the software, so that's been great.

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:15.080
So the executive summary of what this is all about is that if you look at how data science

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:23.679
tools work now, like Base R, NumPy, SciPy, the Python ecosystem, MATLAB, a lot of the

00:02:23.679 --> 00:02:29.199
semantics of how these tools work are based on the way that computational systems worked

00:02:29.199 --> 00:02:36.039
in the 1980s and 1990s, so everything's built on a foundation of 30- to 40-year-old Fortran

00:02:36.039 --> 00:02:38.039
code.

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:47.600
We have seen tools augmented with multi-core algorithms and some more sophisticated execution,

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:54.740
but in general, you have things that are single-core, that evaluate eagerly.

00:02:54.740 --> 00:03:00.339
The language ecosystems are pretty fragmented, so you very rarely see R programmers collaborating

00:03:00.339 --> 00:03:07.199
with Python programmers and sharing libraries of code to power their applications.

00:03:07.199 --> 00:03:10.720
So the world that I would like to see is to be able to take advantage of all this fancy

00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:11.919
hardware that we have now.

00:03:11.919 --> 00:03:17.759
We have graphics cards, we have computers, you can buy a desktop with 16 physical cores

00:03:17.759 --> 00:03:22.000
and 32 virtual cores, so you should be able to take advantage of that.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.500
We can compile code at runtime and generate custom functions that are specialized for

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:33.800
your hardware, but a big part also is that I would like to see the language ecosystems

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:37.520
able to collaborate and share code and data.

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:42.679
So one reason that not as much of this work has happened yet has been because of Moore's

00:03:42.679 --> 00:03:48.600
Law and, you know, if your code runs slow, you can just wait because in a couple of years

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:53.759
your processor will be twice as fast and that has essentially stopped happening, so we need

00:03:53.759 --> 00:03:59.759
to get more out of the hardware that we have because it's not getting that much faster

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:01.199
year over year.

00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:06.119
Although we do have graphics cards, which seemingly are, you know, continuing to scale

00:04:06.119 --> 00:04:11.479
and have thousands of cores on a single graphics card.

00:04:11.479 --> 00:04:18.959
So the Arrow project, so I helped launch the project about three years ago and our central

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:25.640
idea is that we wanted to define a language independent open standard for data frames.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:31.239
And you might say, well, we have data frames in R and data frames in Python, but if you

00:04:31.239 --> 00:04:38.040
look under the hood how those data frames are implemented, how they're arranged in memory,

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:40.720
the memory representation is very different.

00:04:40.720 --> 00:04:45.920
And so as a result of that, you can't really share code and if you want to share data from

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:51.079
one runtime environment to another, you have to serialize, which is very expensive.

00:04:51.079 --> 00:04:56.760
So essentially the view of the world that we would like to see is to have tools able

00:04:56.760 --> 00:05:04.200
to collaborate and work on a common data representation that is not tied to a particular runtime environment

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:07.480
or programming language.

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:14.640
So kind of the bird's eye view, if you think, and where the project is going, and since

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:21.920
I have zero time now, but what I would like to do and the way that we've been building

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:28.799
the community is to bring together the data science world with the analytic database community.

00:05:28.799 --> 00:05:35.119
So a lot of the performance and scalability work in working with big data, I don't know

00:05:35.119 --> 00:05:39.160
if we're still saying big data now, a lot of that work has happened in the analytic

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:44.760
database world and relatively little work has made its way into the data science ecosystem.

00:05:44.760 --> 00:05:49.320
And if you look at the way that database engines are built, typically you interact with them

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:56.600
through SQL or some other frontend API, usually it's SQL queries, but those queries then interact

00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:03.440
with a bunch of components that deal with query execution, in memory, data management,

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:10.200
and interactions with storage and essentially whether it's disk or cloud storage or whatever.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:15.079
So what we were doing in the Arrow project is building a set of high-quality components

00:06:15.079 --> 00:06:21.160
that have public APIs that can be used as the basis of building different kinds of essentially

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:27.040
embedded database engines that can be run on a laptop or run kind of in a distributed

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:29.720
cluster.

00:06:29.720 --> 00:06:34.679
But we aren't really being prescriptive about the frontend, so if you want to build a database,

00:06:34.679 --> 00:06:39.519
you can build a database, if you want to build a data frame library or build something that

00:06:39.519 --> 00:06:45.000
can be used by an R or Python programmer, you can do that as well.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:50.239
So we have three primary use cases, and I'm going to tell you very briefly about how this

00:06:50.239 --> 00:06:56.279
is relevant to R programmers, but the three big things that we're concerned with is getting

00:06:56.279 --> 00:07:03.079
faster access to data, so being able to read and write datasets in the most important file

00:07:03.079 --> 00:07:06.040
formats as fast as possible.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:11.040
We want to be able to move around data as efficiently as possible within a single node,

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:16.799
so between one process and another through shared memory, or moving data between nodes

00:07:16.799 --> 00:07:26.279
in a network through remote procedure calls, so through sockets or other inter-node communication.

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:32.440
The last, so the last thing is that we want to be able to compute analytics, and so if

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:36.320
you're using R, you're using Python, you're already doing analytics every day when you

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:44.200
use data frame libraries, so these would be standardized libraries of algorithms that

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:49.519
could be used in many different scenarios, and we want to be able to take advantage of

00:07:49.519 --> 00:07:55.279
the latest and greatest in compiler technology to be able to do specialization of functions

00:07:55.279 --> 00:08:01.079
to go even faster based on prior knowledge of what you're doing with your data.

00:08:01.079 --> 00:08:03.880
So how is this all relevant to R?

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:11.399
Well, we are building bindings for the Arrow libraries, which are mostly written in C++,

00:08:11.399 --> 00:08:16.799
so that work on the R side has been led by Romain Francois, who you may know from the

00:08:16.799 --> 00:08:20.679
dplyr project.

00:08:20.679 --> 00:08:28.559
So I will talk about R data frames, because I have no time, but the key use cases where

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:33.400
there's a lot of interest in the R world is being able to memory map and interact with

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:37.520
very large on-disk data sets that don't fit into memory.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:42.640
We want to be able to, this is not about replacing dplyr or replacing data.table, it's

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:50.000
about having tools that can be used to accelerate these projects while leaving the user interface,

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.119
like with the code that you write, largely unchanged.

00:08:54.119 --> 00:09:01.400
So you may know about dplyr, dplyr is already a domain-specific language where you write

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:08.580
a sequence of dplyr verbs and expressions, and then those expressions are effectively

00:09:08.580 --> 00:09:13.080
compiled into whatever backend where dplyr is executing.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:21.179
So dplyr can execute against SQL engines or it can execute using its in-memory engine.

00:09:21.179 --> 00:09:27.239
And so what our goal is to do is if you do have a very large data set which is coming

00:09:27.239 --> 00:09:32.239
out of code in the arrow ecosystem, whether it's memory mapped on-disk data, or maybe

00:09:32.239 --> 00:09:38.599
you have a directory of parquet files, or maybe a set of cloud buckets that contain

00:09:38.599 --> 00:09:40.320
parquet files.

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:48.520
So using dplyr, you may have an arrow data set and a collection of dplyr verbs, and so

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:55.039
we can translate these standard dplyr expressions into computation graphs that are evaluated

00:09:55.039 --> 00:10:00.039
by parallel runtime coming out of the arrow project, and we can also do fancy things like

00:10:00.039 --> 00:10:06.619
look at non-standard evaluation, kind of unevaluated R expressions.

00:10:06.619 --> 00:10:12.200
So when you write this in dplyr, these expressions don't get evaluated immediately, but we can

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:21.799
use LLVM to compile these expressions to go even faster against the data sets.

00:10:21.799 --> 00:10:32.640
So anyway, I'm sorry about the AV problems, but these things happen.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:38.940
But anyway, there's a lot of interesting things on the horizon for the project, and I'm excited

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:44.359
to collaborate with the R community, getting the software into production and making your

00:10:44.359 --> 00:10:51.440
data science work faster and more efficient and hopefully a little bit more fun.

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:56.320
So many of you may be aware about three years ago, Hadley and I started the Feather project,

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.340
which uses the arrow technology internally.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:05.599
So another thing we'd like to see is an evolved version of Feather that has more features

00:11:05.599 --> 00:11:09.359
and is faster and more efficient than what is there now.

00:11:09.359 --> 00:11:15.840
So even if you're already a Feather user, even that will be improved eventually.

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:23.080
So anyway, check out the slides, and I'll be around the conference if you'd like to chat.

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:23.580
Thank you.

